Ver comentario de James Demers:
http://www.nytimes.com/2014/10/06/opinion/paul-krugman-voodoo-economics-the-next-generation.html?_r=0
Taxes are not "contractionary" -- that's the bogus assumption at the heart of voodoo economics. Tax receipts are not buried in a hole in the ground - they are returned to the economy when the government purchases goods and services, just as any other economic player does.
Contrast this to what happens when the already-rich are given tax breaks, so that they can get even richer, faster. Aside from the purchase of (more) enormous yachts, there is little evidence that the added income goes toward the GOP's favorite illusion, "job creation." It flows mostly into stock portfolios, overseas accounts, and trust funds. Republicans are in complete denial regarding which of these outcomes is actually "contractionary".

Also: (IMF recommends wealth redistribution)
http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/wonkblog/wp/2014/02/26/communists-have-seized-the-imf/
Much appears to depend on how the redistribution is accomplished. If taxes are raised and the money simply distributed to the less affluent, about the only effect is to increase consumption, although if famine is a problem this may still be be beneficial/necessary IN THE SHORT TERM. If the upper income sectors taxes are significantly raised and the taxes are used to improve education/training, public health, infrastructure (power, roads, utilities, etc.), SME creation/finance, etc. historically not only are the less affluent be helped because of increased income due to expanded employment, the aggregate "quality of life" for the entire nation improves. This however will not occur in a "vacuum." Internal and external trade policies must be adjusted, and internal socioeconomic structure must be modified for any lasting effect, for example not only economic but political power must be redistributed to reflect the current socioeconomic contributions made by each sector. In too many cases the distribution of power/privilage has been largely frozen for several centuries and is no longer operational in this era of globalization and post-industrial economic reality.

